# Introduction

This document demonstrates the advanced elements available in DocLang, including **Mermaid diagrams**, **Chart.js visualizations**, and **Leaflet maps**. These elements enable you to create rich, interactive documentation with complex visualizations.

## Document Overview

The following sections showcase:

- [x] Flowcharts and decision diagrams
- [x] Sequence diagrams for process flows
- [x] Bar charts for data visualization
- [x] Combined charts with multiple data types
- [x] World maps with markers
- [x] Regional maps with custom locations

:::info
**Note**: All diagrams and charts are rendered using industry-standard libraries (Mermaid, Chart.js, Leaflet) ensuring compatibility and high-quality output.
:::

<<pagebreak>>

# 1. Diagram Examples

## 1.1 Flowchart Diagrams

Flowcharts are excellent for representing decision-making processes and workflow logic. The following diagram shows a simple decision flow:

<<mermaid>>
graph TD
    A[Inicio] --> B{¿Decisión?}
    B -->|Sí| C[Hacer algo]
    B -->|No| D[Hacer otra cosa]
    C --> E[Fin]
    D --> E

*Figure 1: Simple flowchart demonstrating decision logic*

### Use Cases for Flowcharts

Flowcharts are ideal for:

- **Process Documentation**: Document business processes and workflows
- **Decision Trees**: Show conditional logic and decision points
- **Algorithm Design**: Visualize algorithmic steps
- **Troubleshooting Guides**: Create step-by-step diagnostic procedures

:::tip
**Best Practice**: Keep flowcharts focused on a single process. For complex systems, create multiple diagrams linked together rather than one massive flowchart.
:::

## 1.2 Sequence Diagrams

Sequence diagrams illustrate the interaction between different components over time. They're particularly useful for documenting API calls, system interactions, and communication protocols.

<<mermaid>>
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as User
    participant S as Server
    participant DB as Database
    
    U->>S: Request
    S->>DB: Query
    DB-->>S: Results
    S-->>U: Response

*Figure 2: Sequence diagram showing client-server-database interaction*

### When to Use Sequence Diagrams

Sequence diagrams excel at showing:

| Use Case | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| **API Documentation** | Document request/response flows between services |
| **Authentication Flows** | Show multi-step authentication processes |
| **Data Processing** | Illustrate how data moves through system components |
| **Error Handling** | Demonstrate exception and error propagation paths |

*Table 1: Common use cases for sequence diagrams*

:::warning
**Important**: Sequence diagrams can become cluttered with too many participants. Limit to 4-6 participants per diagram for optimal readability.
:::

<<pagebreak>>

# 2. Chart Examples

## 2.1 Bar Charts

Bar charts are perfect for comparing discrete categories or showing performance metrics over time periods.

<<chart: bar>>
data: [
  ["Q1", 45, 32, 28],
  ["Q2", 52, 38, 35],
  ["Q3", 61, 45, 42],
  ["Q4", 73, 51, 48]
]
series: ["Product A", "Product B", "Product C"]
options:
  responsive: true
  plugins:
    title:
      display: true
      text: "Quarterly Sales by Product"

*Chart 1: Quarterly sales performance across three product lines*

### Sales Performance Analysis

The chart above demonstrates:

- **Product A** shows consistent growth across all quarters, with Q4 showing the strongest performance
- **Product B** maintains steady mid-range performance with gradual improvement
- **Product C** has the lowest sales but shows positive growth trajectory

**Key Insights:**

1. All products show positive quarter-over-quarter growth
2. Q4 represents the strongest sales period across all products (seasonal trend)
3. Product A outperforms by approximately 40-50% compared to other products

:::tip
**Recommendation**: Focus marketing efforts on Product A strategies to boost performance of Products B and C.
:::

## 2.2 Combined Charts

Combined charts allow you to display multiple chart types in a single visualization, perfect for comparing different data series with varying scales or meanings.

<<chart: combo>>
type: ["bar", "bar", "line"]
data: [
  ["Jan", 65, 28, 45],
  ["Feb", 59, 48, 52],
  ["Mar", 80, 40, 61],
  ["Apr", 81, 19, 73]
]
series: ["Desktop", "Mobile", "Total"]
options:
  responsive: true
  plugins:
    legend:
      position: top
    title:
      display: true
      text: "Traffic by Device"

*Chart 2: Website traffic distribution by device type with total trend line*

### Traffic Analysis Summary

The combined chart illustrates web traffic patterns:

| Month | Desktop | Mobile | Total | Mobile % |
|-------|---------|--------|-------|----------|
| January | 65K | 28K | 45K | 30.1% |
| February | 59K | 48K | 52K | 44.9% |
| March | 80K | 40K | 61K | 33.3% |
| April | 81K | 19K | 73K | 19.0% |

*Table 2: Detailed traffic breakdown by device category*

**Observations:**

- Desktop traffic remains relatively stable (59-81K range)
- Mobile traffic shows high volatility (19-48K range)
- Total traffic shows upward trend (45K → 73K)
- Mobile percentage varies significantly month-to-month

:::warning
**Action Required**: Investigate the sharp drop in mobile traffic during April. Potential causes could include:
- Technical issues with mobile site
- Algorithm changes affecting mobile search rankings
- Seasonal behavior patterns
- Mobile app migration
:::

